<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-08-12T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-08-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="368" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d368">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">890.20/8–1249: Airgram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Taipei</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Macdonald</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Taipei</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-08-12">August 12,
                                        1949</date>.<lb/>[Received August 24—5:18 p. m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>A–75. Assistant Military Attaché, Taipei, Captain Manning, told me
                                that the Generalissimo’s son made the remark to him and several
                                other people that after the Pacific Union is formed the Philippines
                                and Korea will receive American assistance after which China will be
                                able to get aid through them.</p>
                            <p>This apparently is the general line of Chinese thinking at present
                                and was expressed yesterday at an interview granted to Handleman of
                                I. N. S. by K. C. Wu who stated: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                    <p>“The release of the White Paper<note n="1" xml:id="d368fn1">August 5; see <ref target="frus1949v09#pg_1365">vol.
                                                  <hi rend="smallcaps">ix</hi>, pp. 1365</ref>
                                            ff.</note> by the State Department exposes the unwise
                                        and impractical U.S. policy; but it is hoped that the U.S.
                                        can extend indirect assistance to China through the Pacific
                                        Union.”</p>
                                </quote>
                            </p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Macdonald</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>